This paper is primarily focused on visual tracking, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The use of a probabilistic graph model and dynamic programming method suggests a strong emphasis on machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) techniques. Additionally, the paper's focus on tracking interacting objects and recovering complete trajectories suggests a potential overlap with robotics (cs.RO) and control (cs.CR) sub-categories. Finally, the use of probabilistic models and optimization techniques suggests a potential overlap with the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
